  <graph edgedefault="directed">
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2194775991">
      <data key="d1">The article presents a residual learning framework that simplifies the training of significantly deeper neural networks, demonstrating that these networks can achieve higher accuracy with lower complexity. It highlights empirical results from the ImageNet dataset, where a deep residual network achieved a 3.57% error rate, winning first place in the ILSVRC 2015 classification task, and shows improvements in object detection on the COCO dataset.</data>
      <data key="d2">G1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2163605009">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the development and training of a deep convolutional neural network that achieved significant improvements in image classification accuracy on the ImageNet dataset, achieving top-1 and top-5 error rates of 37.5% and 17.0%, respectively. It highlights the network's architecture, including its use of non-saturating neurons and dropout regularization, and notes its success in the ILSVRC-2012 competition, where it outperformed other entries.</data>
      <data key="d2">G2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1951724000">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the use of the lme4 package in R for fitting linear mixed-effects models, detailing the process of obtaining maximum likelihood and restricted maximum likelihood estimates through the lmer function. It covers the structure of the models, the evaluation of criteria for parameter estimation, and provides guidance for users interested in creating specialized mixed models, including those with complex features like pedigrees and smoothing splines.</data>
      <data key="d2">G3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2101234009">
      <data key="d1">The article provides an overview of Scikit-learn, a Python module that offers a comprehensive collection of advanced machine learning algorithms for both supervised and unsupervised tasks, designed for ease of use by non-specialists. It highlights the package's focus on performance, documentation, and API consistency, while also noting its minimal dependencies and availability for academic and commercial use.</data>
      <data key="d2">G4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2112778345">
      <data key="d1">The CES-D scale is a validated self-report tool designed to assess depressive symptoms in the general population, demonstrating high internal consistency and reliability across diverse demographic groups, making it a valuable resource for epidemiological studies on depression.</data>
      <data key="d2">G5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2962835968">
      <data key="d1">The article explores the impact of increasing the depth of convolutional networks on accuracy in large-scale image recognition, demonstrating that using very small (3x3) convolution filters can significantly enhance performance with networks of 16-19 weight layers. The findings contributed to a successful submission in the ImageNet Challenge 2014, and the authors have made their top-performing models publicly available to support further research in deep learning and computer vision.</data>
      <data key="d2">G6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W3023540311">
      <data key="d1">This book serves as a comprehensive guide to genetic algorithms, offering practical insights and examples for students and practitioners in various fields. It covers essential concepts and applications in search, optimization, and machine learning, using Pascal programs to illustrate key ideas without requiring prior knowledge of genetics or advanced mathematics.</data>
      <data key="d2">G7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2112796928">
      <data key="d1">The article reviews gradient-based learning techniques, particularly multilayer neural networks and convolutional networks, for document recognition, focusing on their application in character recognition tasks. It highlights the effectiveness of a new paradigm called graph transformer (GTN) for optimizing multimodule systems and discusses the commercial deployment of these methods in reading bank cheques with high accuracy.</data>
      <data key="d2">G8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1686810756">
      <data key="d1">The article explores the impact of increasing the depth of convolutional networks on accuracy in large-scale image recognition, demonstrating that architectures with 16-19 layers using small (3x3) convolution filters can significantly outperform previous models. The findings contributed to a successful submission in the ImageNet Challenge 2014, and the authors have made their top-performing models publicly available to support further research in deep learning and computer vision.</data>
      <data key="d2">G9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2097117768">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces the Inception architecture, specifically the GoogLeNet model, which achieved state-of-the-art results in the 2014 ImageNet competition by optimizing the depth and width of convolutional neural networks while maintaining computational efficiency, leveraging multi-scale processing principles.</data>
      <data key="d2">G10</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1995945562">
      <data key="d1">This article introduces bootstrap methods for statistical estimation, providing straightforward explanations and Minitab macros for practical implementation. It covers key concepts in statistical inference and resampling techniques relevant to fields such as data science and machine learning.</data>
      <data key="d2">G11</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W3015634246">
      <data key="d1">The article provides an applications-oriented introduction to multivariate data analysis, emphasizing practical techniques over mathematical derivations. It outlines a six-step framework for organizing various analytical methods, including factor analysis, multiple regression, and emerging techniques, making it accessible for non-statisticians while covering essential concepts and applications in data science.</data>
      <data key="d2">G12</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2963446712">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces Dense Convolutional Networks (DenseNet), a novel architecture that enhances convolutional networks by connecting each layer to every other layer in a feed-forward manner, resulting in improved accuracy, efficiency, and reduced parameters. The authors demonstrate DenseNet's effectiveness on several object recognition benchmarks, achieving significant performance gains over existing state-of-the-art methods while minimizing memory and computational requirements.</data>
      <data key="d2">G13</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2095705004">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the dropout technique, a method used to prevent overfitting in deep neural networks by randomly removing units during training, which enhances model performance across various supervised tasks such as vision, speech recognition, and document classification. This approach not only reduces computational complexity but also yields significant improvements over traditional regularization methods, achieving state-of-the-art results on benchmark datasets.</data>
      <data key="d2">G14</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1663973292">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the publication of peer-reviewed research papers in the *Journal of Electronic Imaging*, focusing on advancements in electronic imaging science and technology, with an emphasis on statistical and temporal pattern recognition, machine learning applications, and data science in image analysis.</data>
      <data key="d2">G15</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2124776405">
      <data key="d1">&quot;Neural Networks: A Comprehensive Foundation&quot; offers an in-depth exploration of neural networks from an engineering perspective, covering essential topics such as learning processes, back-propagation, and VLSI implementation. This well-organized and accessible text is designed for professional engineers and graduate students, featuring practical examples, problems, and illustrations to reinforce key concepts in the field of neural computation and machine learning.</data>
      <data key="d2">G16</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2140190241">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the third edition of &quot;Data Mining: Concepts and Techniques,&quot; highlighting its focus on advanced data mining tools and techniques necessary for transforming large data sets into actionable knowledge. It covers new topics such as data warehouses, social networks, and multimedia data, while providing practical examples and algorithms for real-world applications in various fields.</data>
      <data key="d2">G17</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2618530766">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the training of a deep convolutional neural network to classify 1.2 million images from the ImageNet LSVRC-2010 contest into 1000 categories, achieving significant improvements in error rates compared to previous models. It highlights the network's architecture, including its use of dropout for regularization and efficient GPU implementation, which contributed to its success in the ILSVRC-2012 competition.</data>
      <data key="d2">G18</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1903029394">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the development and application of fully convolutional networks (FCNs) for semantic segmentation, demonstrating that these networks can outperform state-of-the-art methods by processing images of arbitrary sizes and producing correspondingly-sized outputs. It highlights the architecture's ability to combine features from different layers for improved segmentation accuracy and its effectiveness on benchmark datasets like PASCAL VOC and NYUDv2.</data>
      <data key="d2">G19</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2105934661">
      <data key="d1">The article presents a novel approach to linear filtering and prediction problems by utilizing the Bode-Shannon representation of random processes and state-transition method analysis. It introduces new formulation methods applicable to both stationary and nonstationary statistics, derives a nonlinear equation for optimal estimation error, and discusses its implications for existing problems in the field, all while providing a self-contained review of fundamental concepts.</data>
      <data key="d2">G20</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2121863487">
      <data key="d1">&quot;Reinforcement Learning: An Introduction&quot; by Richard Sutton and Andrew Barto offers a comprehensive overview of reinforcement learning, detailing its foundational concepts, key algorithms, and recent advancements in the field. The book is structured into three parts, covering Markov decision processes, solution methods, and a unified perspective that integrates neural networks and planning, while also discussing practical applications and future directions in artificial intelligence.</data>
      <data key="d2">G21</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2963037989">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces YOLO (You Only Look Once), a novel approach to real-time object detection that frames the task as a regression problem, allowing a single neural network to predict bounding boxes and class probabilities directly from full images in one evaluation. YOLO achieves remarkable speed, processing 45 frames per second with its base model and 155 frames per second with a smaller version, while demonstrating strong performance in generalizing across various domains compared to existing methods.</data>
      <data key="d2">G22</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2148603752">
      <data key="d1">The article provides an overview of Statistical Learning Theory, focusing on the principles of learning and generalization from empirical data. It discusses methods for selecting optimal functions based on limited data and their practical applications in various fields of computer science and robotics.</data>
      <data key="d2">G23</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W639708223">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces Faster R-CNN, a novel object detection framework that utilizes Region Proposal Networks (RPN) to generate high-quality object proposals with minimal computational cost, achieving real-time performance and state-of-the-art accuracy on benchmark datasets. By integrating deep learning techniques and sharing convolutional features, the system significantly enhances detection speed while maintaining high precision, making it a leading solution in the field of computer vision.</data>
      <data key="d2">G24</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2134967712">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces AutoDock Vina, a molecular docking and virtual screening program that significantly enhances speed and accuracy in binding mode predictions through a new scoring function, efficient optimization, and multithreading capabilities, achieving a remarkable two orders of magnitude improvement over its predecessor, AutoDock 4.</data>
      <data key="d2">G25</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1573234480">
      <data key="d1">&quot;Discovering Statistics Using SPSS&quot; is a comprehensive guide tailored for students using SAS, featuring updated commands and programming from SAS 9.2. Co-authored by Andy Field and Jeremy Miles, the book presents statistical methods and tests in an engaging style, supported by interactive examples and a companion website with research datasets, making it suitable for both intermediate and advanced courses.</data>
      <data key="d2">G26</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2102605133">
      <data key="d1">The article presents a novel algorithm, R-CNN, that significantly enhances object detection and semantic segmentation performance on the PASCAL VOC dataset by over 30% compared to previous methods. It leverages high-capacity convolutional neural networks for region proposals and emphasizes the benefits of supervised pre-training with domain-specific fine-tuning when labeled data is limited.</data>
      <data key="d2">G27</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2125055259">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses &quot;C4.5: Programs for Machine Learning,&quot; a comprehensive guide by Ross Quinlan that details the C4.5 algorithm for classification in machine learning. It covers the implementation of the algorithm in a UNIX environment, provides source code, and includes case studies demonstrating its effectiveness in handling various data types and challenges, making it a valuable resource for developers and students in the field of machine learning.</data>
      <data key="d2">G28</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2183341477">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses advancements in the Inception architecture for computer vision, focusing on optimizing convolutional networks to enhance efficiency while maintaining high performance. It highlights the use of factorized convolutions and aggressive regularization to achieve significant improvements in classification accuracy on the ILSVRC 2012 dataset, demonstrating a balance between model size and computational cost.</data>
      <data key="d2">G29</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2099471712">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces a novel framework for estimating generative models using Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs), where two models are trained simultaneously: a generator that captures the data distribution and a discriminator that evaluates the authenticity of samples. The approach leverages a minimax game strategy, allowing for efficient training without the need for Markov chains or approximate inference networks, and demonstrates promising results through qualitative and quantitative evaluations.</data>
      <data key="d2">G30</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2035618305">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces clusterProfiler, an R package designed for automating biological-term classification enrichment analysis of gene clusters, facilitating the analysis of increasing data from transcriptomics and proteomics. It supports multiple species, including humans, mice, and yeast, and offers a reusable workflow for visualizing biological themes, with its source code available through the Bioconductor project.</data>
      <data key="d2">G31</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1594031697">
      <data key="d1">This article explores the methodology behind constructing classification and regression trees, highlighting both practical applications and theoretical foundations. It emphasizes the significance of tree-structured rules in data analysis, particularly in the context of machine learning and statistical inference, and discusses their fundamental properties and implications in various fields such as data science and pattern recognition.</data>
      <data key="d2">G32</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2148698435">
      <data key="d1">The article announces the release of MrBayes 3.2, a significant upgrade to the popular software for Bayesian phylogenetic inference, highlighting its enhanced features such as improved convergence diagnostics, parallel analysis capabilities, faster likelihood calculations through GPU support, and new modeling options for evolutionary analysis. It emphasizes the software's advancements in efficiency and flexibility for researchers in evolutionary biology and related fields.</data>
      <data key="d2">G33</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2148143831">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique (SMOTE) as a method for improving classifier performance on imbalanced datasets, where minority classes are underrepresented. It highlights the effectiveness of combining over-sampling of minority classes with under-sampling of majority classes to enhance sensitivity and achieve better results in classification tasks, particularly in terms of the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve.</data>
      <data key="d2">G34</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W3118608800">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the training of a multi-layer generative model using a dataset of millions of tiny color images, specifically focusing on Restricted Boltzmann Machines (RBMs) and Deep Belief Networks (DBNs) to learn effective image features and improve classification performance compared to raw pixel data. It highlights the challenges faced by previous attempts in this area and emphasizes the significance of the CIFAR-10 dataset in the research.</data>
      <data key="d2">G35</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1536680647">
      <data key="d1">The article presents Fast R-CNN, an advanced method for object detection that enhances the efficiency and accuracy of classifying image proposals using deep convolutional networks, achieving significant improvements in training and testing speeds compared to previous models like R-CNN and SPPnet. Implemented in Python and C++, Fast R-CNN is available as open-source software under the MIT License.</data>
      <data key="d2">G36</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1678356000">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the concept of greedy function approximation through gradient boosting machines, emphasizing a numerical optimization approach to function estimation. It explores the connection between stagewise additive expansions and steepest-descent minimization, presenting specific algorithms for various regression and classification tasks, while highlighting the robustness and interpretability of gradient boosting trees in handling less clean data.</data>
      <data key="d2">G37</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2121044470">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces a straightforward sequentially rejective multiple test procedure that allows for the rejection of hypotheses one at a time, ensuring control over the first kind error rate across various true hypothesis combinations. It also explores the power properties of the method and its potential applications in fields such as statistics, computer science, and machine learning.</data>
      <data key="d2">G38</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2963150697">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces Mask R-CNN, a versatile framework for object instance segmentation that enhances the Faster R-CNN model by adding a branch for predicting segmentation masks alongside bounding box recognition. It demonstrates superior performance across various tasks, including segmentation and keypoint detection, while maintaining efficiency and ease of training, positioning it as a strong baseline for future research in instance-level tasks.</data>
      <data key="d2">G39</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1836465849">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses Batch Normalization, a technique designed to address the issue of internal covariate shift in deep neural networks, which complicates training by altering the distribution of layer inputs. By normalizing inputs within mini-batches, this method accelerates training, allows for higher learning rates, and can even reduce the need for regularization techniques like Dropout, ultimately achieving significant improvements in model accuracy on tasks such as image classification.</data>
      <data key="d2">G40</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1554663460">
      <data key="d1">This article provides a comprehensive overview of feed-forward neural networks in the context of statistical pattern recognition, covering essential concepts, modeling techniques, error functions, and learning algorithms, while also including over 100 exercises for practical application. It serves as a valuable resource for professionals and students in fields such as computer science, machine learning, and data science.</data>
      <data key="d2">G41</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1554944419">
      <data key="d1">&quot;The Elements of Statistical Learning&quot; is a comprehensive resource that explores the intersection of statistics, data mining, and machine learning, emphasizing conceptual understanding over mathematical complexity. Authored by renowned statisticians, the book covers a wide range of topics, including supervised and unsupervised learning techniques, and introduces advanced methods such as graphical models and ensemble methods, making it valuable for both statisticians and practitioners in various fields.</data>
      <data key="d2">G42</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2891378911">
      <data key="d1">The article presents the PRISMA Extension for Scoping Reviews (PRISMA-ScR), a checklist designed to enhance the methodological reporting quality of scoping reviews by outlining 20 essential items and optional components, along with explanations and examples for each. Developed by a panel of experts, the checklist aims to improve understanding among various stakeholders, including researchers and policymakers, regarding the key elements necessary for effective reporting in scoping reviews.</data>
      <data key="d2">G43</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2953106684">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces Faster R-CNN, a novel object detection framework that utilizes Region Proposal Networks (RPN) to generate high-quality region proposals with minimal computational cost, significantly improving detection speed and accuracy. By integrating full-image convolutional features and employing neural attention mechanisms, the system achieves state-of-the-art performance on benchmark datasets while maintaining a frame rate of 5fps on a deep VGG-16 model.</data>
      <data key="d2">G44</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2165698076">
      <data key="d1">This article provides a comprehensive survey on transfer learning, highlighting its significance in addressing the challenges of differing feature spaces and distributions in real-world machine learning applications. It categorizes current advancements in transfer learning for various tasks such as classification, regression, and clustering, while also discussing its relationship with related techniques and potential research issues.</data>
      <data key="d2">G45</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2105846236">
      <data key="d1">The article critiques traditional methods for assessing discriminant validity in variance-based structural equation modeling, such as the Fornell-Larcker criterion and cross-loadings, highlighting their unreliability in common research scenarios. It proposes a new approach using the heterotrait-monotrait ratio correlations, demonstrating its effectiveness through simulation studies and offering guidelines for improved modeling practices.</data>
      <data key="d2">G46</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2111647009">
      <data key="d1">The article presents IQ-TREE, a fast and effective stochastic algorithm designed for estimating maximum-likelihood phylogenies from large phylogenomic datasets. It highlights the algorithm's ability to efficiently explore tree-space and achieve higher likelihoods compared to existing programs, making it a valuable tool for evolutionary biology and bioinformatics.</data>
      <data key="d2">G47</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2122410182">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the revised edition of a leading textbook on artificial intelligence, which provides a comprehensive introduction to both the theoretical foundations and practical applications of AI, covering topics such as intelligent agents, problem-solving, logical reasoning, and machine learning. It is aimed at computer professionals, linguists, and cognitive scientists interested in the field of artificial intelligence.</data>
      <data key="d2">G48</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2109606373">
      <data key="d1">The article &quot;Smoothing and Differentiation of Data by Simplified Least Squares Procedures&quot; by Abraham Savitzky and M. J. E. Golay discusses methods for data smoothing and differentiation using simplified least squares techniques, highlighting their applications in statistical analysis and data modeling. It presents a systematic approach to enhance data interpretation through effective curve fitting and approximation methods.</data>
      <data key="d2">G49</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2100495367">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the use of multilayer neural networks, specifically autoencoders, for reducing high-dimensional data to low-dimensional representations, highlighting an effective initialization method that enhances their performance compared to traditional principal components analysis. It emphasizes the importance of gradient descent in fine-tuning the network weights for improved learning outcomes in dimensionality reduction tasks.</data>
      <data key="d2">G50</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2565639579">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the development of Feature Pyramid Networks (FPN) for object detection, which enhances the ability to recognize objects at various scales using a top-down architecture with lateral connections. The proposed method demonstrates significant improvements in detection accuracy on the COCO benchmark while maintaining practical computational efficiency, achieving state-of-the-art results without excessive complexity.</data>
      <data key="d2">G51</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1499170180">
      <data key="d1">This chapter on multivariate data analysis covers a range of statistical methodologies and techniques, including graphical data presentation, clustering algorithms, principal component analysis, and regression methods, aimed at effectively analyzing and interpreting complex datasets in data science and machine learning.</data>
      <data key="d2">G52</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2949117887">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses Batch Normalization, a technique designed to address the issue of internal covariate shift in deep neural networks, which complicates training by altering the distribution of layer inputs. By normalizing inputs within mini-batches, this method accelerates training, allows for higher learning rates, and can even reduce the need for regularization techniques like Dropout, ultimately achieving state-of-the-art results in image classification tasks.</data>
      <data key="d2">G53</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2962793481">
      <data key="d1">The article presents a novel approach to unpaired image-to-image translation using Cycle-Consistent Adversarial Networks, enabling the learning of mappings between source and target image domains without the need for aligned training pairs. It highlights the effectiveness of the method through qualitative results in various applications, such as style transfer and photo enhancement, and demonstrates its superiority over previous techniques through quantitative comparisons.</data>
      <data key="d2">G54</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2157331557">
      <data key="d1">The article presents a novel approach to statistical machine translation by utilizing RNN encoder-decoder architectures to learn phrase representations, enhancing the effectiveness of language modeling and translation tasks in natural language processing. The authors explore the implications of this method within the broader context of deep learning and machine learning research.</data>
      <data key="d2">G55</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2963163009">
      <data key="d1">The article presents MobileNetV2, a novel mobile architecture that enhances performance across various tasks and model sizes by utilizing inverted residuals and linear bottlenecks. It also introduces SSDLite for object detection and Mobile DeepLabv3 for semantic segmentation, emphasizing the importance of maintaining representational power while optimizing efficiency through lightweight depthwise convolutions.</data>
      <data key="d2">G56</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W273955616">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the concept of ensemble learning, focusing on the random forests method, which enhances traditional bagging by introducing additional randomness in the construction of decision trees. It highlights the advantages of random forests, such as robustness against overfitting and ease of use, while also providing an overview of the randomForest package in R for implementing this classification and regression technique.</data>
      <data key="d2">G57</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1639032689">
      <data key="d1">This book serves as an accessible guide to genetic algorithms, providing students and practitioners with the necessary computer techniques and mathematical tools to apply these algorithms across various fields. It features practical examples, primarily using Pascal programs, and requires only a basic understanding of programming and mathematics.</data>
      <data key="d2">G58</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2964308564">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses a novel approach to neural machine translation that enhances the traditional encoder-decoder architecture by incorporating a mechanism for soft alignment, allowing the model to automatically identify relevant parts of the source sentence when predicting target words. This method achieves performance comparable to state-of-the-art phrase-based systems in English-to-French translation, while also providing intuitive alignment insights.</data>
      <data key="d2">G59</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2963073614">
      <data key="d1">The article explores the use of conditional adversarial networks as a versatile approach for image-to-image translation tasks, demonstrating their effectiveness in synthesizing images from label maps, reconstructing objects from edges, and colorizing images. It highlights the potential of this method to eliminate the need for hand-engineered functions, as evidenced by the creative experiments shared by users of the associated software.</data>
      <data key="d2">G60</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2019207321">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the architecture and learning procedures of the Adaptive-Network-Based Fuzzy Inference System (ANFIS), highlighting its ability to model nonlinear functions and predict chaotic time series through a hybrid approach that combines human knowledge with data. It also compares ANFIS to traditional artificial neural networks and suggests potential applications in automatic signal processing.</data>
      <data key="d2">G61</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2136922672">
      <data key="d1">The article presents a fast learning algorithm for deep belief networks that utilizes complementary priors to overcome inference challenges in densely connected networks with multiple hidden layers. By employing a greedy layer-wise training approach and a fine-tuning process, the algorithm effectively models the joint distribution of handwritten digit images and their labels, achieving superior classification performance compared to traditional discriminative methods.</data>
      <data key="d2">G62</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1990074132">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces Arlequin suite version 3.5, a comprehensive set of programs for population genetics analyses available on both Linux and Windows platforms, featuring enhanced XML output, integrated graphics, and new methods for detecting loci selection. It includes graphical and command-line interfaces, with capabilities for handling large datasets and generating simulated data within an Approximate Bayesian Computation framework.</data>
      <data key="d2">G63</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2963881378">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces SegNet, a deep convolutional encoder-decoder architecture designed for semantic pixel-wise image segmentation, which efficiently utilizes a VGG16-based structure to perform non-linear upsampling using pooling indices. It highlights SegNet's competitive performance in memory efficiency and accuracy compared to other architectures, making it suitable for scene understanding applications.</data>
      <data key="d2">G64</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1677182931">
      <data key="d1">The article explores advancements in rectifier networks for image classification, introducing the Parametric Linear Unit (PReLU) to enhance model fitting with minimal computational cost and risk of overfitting. It also presents a robust initialization method for training deep models, achieving a groundbreaking 4.94% top-5 test error on the ImageNet 2012 dataset, surpassing human-level performance for the first time.</data>
      <data key="d2">G65</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2053186076">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces Locally Linear Embedding (LLE), an unsupervised learning algorithm designed for nonlinear dimensionality reduction, which creates low-dimensional representations of high-dimensional data while preserving local neighborhood structures. LLE distinguishes itself by mapping inputs into a single global coordinate system, enabling the analysis of complex data structures such as images and text documents.</data>
      <data key="d2">G66</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1563088657">
      <data key="d1">This article provides a comprehensive introduction to Support Vector Machines (SVMs), highlighting their effectiveness in various real-world applications such as text categorization and image classification. It serves as a valuable resource for both students and practitioners, offering a thorough understanding of the theory and practical applications of SVMs and related kernel-based learning methods.</data>
      <data key="d2">G67</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2121960517">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the software 'EZR' (Easy R), a user-friendly statistical tool designed for medical statistics, particularly in hematopoietic stem cell transplantation studies. It highlights EZR's capabilities for conducting various analyses, such as survival analyses and sample size calculations, through a point-and-click interface, making it accessible for clinicians without programming expertise.</data>
      <data key="d2">G68</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2138451337">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the development of a near-real-time facial recognition system that utilizes a two-dimensional approach to identify individuals by comparing their facial features to a database of known faces, leveraging eigenfaces as a method for efficient image representation and recognition. The system is designed to operate effectively within practical performance requirements, incorporating elements of machine learning and neural networks for improved accuracy and adaptability.</data>
      <data key="d2">G69</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2965373594">
      <data key="d1">The article discusses the RoBERTa model, a robustly optimized version of BERT, highlighting a replication study that emphasizes the significance of hyperparameter choices and training data size in achieving state-of-the-art performance on various NLP benchmarks. It also raises questions about previously reported improvements in language model pretraining and provides access to the models and code used in the study.</data>
      <data key="d2">G70</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2613718673">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces Faster R-CNN, a novel object detection framework that utilizes Region Proposal Networks (RPN) to generate high-quality region proposals with minimal computational cost, significantly improving detection speed and accuracy. By sharing convolutional features across the network, the system achieves state-of-the-art performance on benchmark datasets while maintaining a frame rate of 5fps using a deep VGG-16 model.</data>
      <data key="d2">G71</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W4211049957">
      <data key="d1">The article provides a comprehensive introduction to Gaussian processes (GPs) in machine learning, covering both theoretical and practical aspects, including supervised learning for regression and classification, model selection, and connections to other statistical techniques. It is aimed at researchers and students in applied statistics, featuring detailed algorithms, a variety of covariance functions, and illustrative examples, along with supplementary resources available online.</data>
      <data key="d2">G72</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W3017143921">
      <data key="d1">The article offers a comprehensive overview of statistical methods for pattern recognition and scene analysis, covering topics such as Bayesian decision theory, supervised and unsupervised learning, and various techniques for image analysis and classification within the fields of computer science and machine learning.</data>
      <data key="d2">G73</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W2531409750">
      <data key="d1">The article introduces Xception, a novel deep learning architecture that enhances the Inception module by utilizing depthwise separable convolutions, leading to improved performance on the ImageNet dataset without increasing the number of parameters. This approach demonstrates a more efficient use of model parameters, resulting in superior image classification capabilities.</data>
      <data key="d2">G74</data>
    </node>
    <node id="https://openalex.org/W1506342804">
      <data key="d1">The article provides a comprehensive overview of iterative methods for solving sparse linear systems, covering foundational concepts in linear algebra, discretization techniques for partial differential equations, and various advanced methods such as preconditioning, multigrid, and domain decomposition, along with their applications in computational science and machine learning.</data>
      <data key="d2">G75</data>
    </node>
