      <data key="d3">In 2018, article MobileNetV2: Inverted Residuals and Linear Bottlenecks was published and referenced article Inception-v4, Inception-ResNet and the Impact of Residual Connections on Learning that was published in 2016</data>
      <data key="d4">The child paper, &quot;MobileNetV2: Inverted Residuals and Linear Bottlenecks,&quot; builds on the concepts introduced in the parent paper, &quot;Inception-v4, Inception-ResNet and the Impact of Residual Connections on Learning,&quot; by utilizing the idea of residual connections and expanding it into a new mobile architecture that enhances performance across various tasks. It extends the parent paper's findings by applying these principles to develop efficient models for object detection and semantic segmentation, demonstrating a novel approach to network design.</data>
