      <data key="d3">In 2017, article Aggregated Residual Transformations for Deep Neural Networks was published and referenced article Inception-v4, Inception-ResNet and the Impact of Residual Connections on Learning that was published in 2016</data>
      <data key="d4">The child paper, &quot;Aggregated Residual Transformations for Deep Neural Networks,&quot; builds on the concepts introduced in the parent paper, &quot;Inception-v4, Inception-ResNet and the Impact of Residual Connections on Learning,&quot; by proposing a new network architecture (ResNeXt) that incorporates and extends the idea of residual connections to improve image classification performance. It empirically demonstrates that its approach, which emphasizes cardinality as a key factor, outperforms the parent paper's architectures under similar conditions.</data>
